		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">UTF-8</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>UTF-8</b> (8-<a href="/wiki/Bit" title="Bit">bit</a> <a href="/wiki/Universal_Character_Set" title="Universal Character Set">UCS</a>/<a href="/wiki/Comparison_of_Unicode_encodings" title="Comparison of Unicode encodings">Unicode Transformation Format</a>) is a <a href="/wiki/Variable-width_encoding" title="Variable-width encoding">variable-length</a> <a href="/wiki/Character_encoding" title="Character encoding">character encoding</a> for <a href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</a>. It is able to represent any character in the Unicode standard, yet the initial encoding of byte codes and character assignments for UTF-8 is <a href="/wiki/Backward_compatibility" title="Backward compatibility">backwards compatible</a> with <a href="/wiki/ASCII" title="ASCII">ASCII</a>. For these reasons, it is steadily becoming the preferred encoding for <a href="/wiki/E-mail" title="E-mail">e-mail</a>, <a href="/wiki/Web_page" title="Web page">web pages</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-GoogleUnicode_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GoogleUnicode-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and other places where characters are <a href="/wiki/Computer_data_storage" title="Computer data storage">stored</a> or <a href="/wiki/Stream_(computing)" title="Stream (computing)">streamed</a>.</p>
<p>UTF-8 encodes each character (<a href="/wiki/Universal_Character_Set" title="Universal Character Set">code point</a>) in one to four <a href="/wiki/Octet_(computing)" title="Octet (computing)">octets</a> (8-bit <a href="/wiki/Byte" title="Byte">bytes</a>), with the 1-byte encoding used for the 128 US-ASCII characters. See the Description section below for details.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Internet_Engineering_Task_Force" title="Internet Engineering Task Force">Internet Engineering Task Force</a> (IETF) requires all <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a> <a href="/wiki/Protocol_(computing)" title="Protocol (computing)">protocols</a> to identify the <a href="/wiki/Character_encoding" title="Character encoding">encoding</a> used for character data, and the supported character encodings must include UTF-8.<sup id="cite_ref-rfc2277_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rfc2277-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Internet_Mail_Consortium" title="Internet Mail Consortium">Internet Mail Consortium</a> (IMC) recommends that all email programs be able to display and create mail using UTF-8.<sup id="cite_ref-IMC_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IMC-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
